# Code Quality Standards

## Naming
- Names describe intent, not implementation: `remainingRetries`, not `counter2`.
- Booleans read as predicates: `isLoading`, `hasError`, `canSubmit`.
- Functions are verbs (`fetchForecast`), values are nouns (`forecast`).
- No abbreviations except universally known ones (`id`, `url`, `db`, `req/res`).
- Match the casing convention already used in the file/project — do not introduce a second style.

## Functions & Structure
- One function = one job. If you need "and" to describe it, split it.
- Prefer early returns over nested if/else pyramids. Max ~3 levels of nesting.
- Keep functions under ~40 lines as a soft limit; extract when a block needs its own comment to be understood.
- Pure logic separated from I/O and side effects wherever practical — it's what makes code testable.
- Avoid premature abstraction: duplicate twice, abstract on the third occurrence, and only when the copies are truly the same concept.

## Errors
- Never swallow errors. Empty `catch` blocks are forbidden.
- Handle errors at the level that can do something about them; re-throw or propagate otherwise.
- Error messages must contain enough context to debug: what was attempted, with what input, what failed.
- Validate at boundaries (user input, API responses, file reads); trust data inside your own core.
- Fail fast and loud in development; degrade gracefully with user-friendly messaging in UI code.

## Comments
- Comment WHY, never WHAT. `// increment i` is noise; `// API returns 1-indexed pages` is signal.
- Document invariants, gotchas, and units (`timeoutMs`, `priceInCents`) — the things code can't say.
- Delete commented-out code; git remembers it.
- Public APIs / exported functions get a short doc comment: purpose, params that aren't obvious, failure modes.

## Dependencies
- Prefer stdlib and existing project dependencies over adding new packages.
- Before adding a dependency, justify it in one line: what it does that ~30 lines of our own code can't.
- Never pin to `latest`; use the version range style the project already uses.

## Magic Values
- No magic numbers/strings used twice — name them as constants.
- Configuration (URLs, keys, limits) lives in config/env, never hardcoded inline.
